er, a revered high-school English teacher who was timid outside the classroom, introduced him to the rich world of literature--and also passed on to him his doubts and insecurities. Freedman retraces his intellectual formation as a student, educator, scholar, and leader, from his early?obsession with book collecting through his undergraduate years at Harvard and his professional training at Yale Law School. This same passion for language and ideas defined Freedman's leadership at Dartmouth, where he deftly countered lingering anti-Semitism, fought entrenched interests to open the way for women and minorities, reformed and revitalized the curriculum, and boldly reconceived the school's campus. This moving and inspiring book vividly depicts the formative years of a man nourished by lifelong learning, whose rise from humble beginnings to heights of achievement will serve as a model for generations to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCollege presidentszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh  aA Handful of Dust.  aAdolescence.  aAlan Dershowitz.  aArchibald MacLeish.  aBachelor's degree.  aBaker v. Carr.  aBiopsy.  aBrown v. Board of Education.  aCareer.  aCarl Sandburg.  aCharles Dickens.  aCivil procedure.  aClass president.  aClassroom.  aColumbia Law School.  aConstitutional law.  aCriticism.  aCurriculum.  aDartmouth College.  aDavid Halberstam.  aDavid Riesman.  aDormitory.  aEmbarrassment.  aEmily Dickinson.  aErnest Hemingway.  aF. Scott Fitzgerald.  aFelix Frankfurter.  aFranklin D. Roosevelt.  aFreedman.  aG. (novel).  aGordon Kahn.  aHarvard College.  aHarvard Law School.  aHarvard University.  aHerbert Wechsler.  aJews.  aJohn F. Kennedy.  aJohn P. Marquand.  aJohn Steinbeck.  aJohnny Tremain.  aJoseph Con